{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480955"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"129"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/129"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.53,0.1,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/129"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36622"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44611"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 66-year-old man presents with a two month history of worsening lower urinary tract symptoms. The physical examination is unremarkable apart from digital rectal examination, where there is a firm and irregular area of enlargement of the left lobe of the prostate. The serum prostate-specific antigen is 22 ng/ml (0-4).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["PSMA-PET scan (prostate specific membrane antigen)","Multi-parametric MRI","Urinary tract ultrasound","Whole body bone scan","Urine cytology"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is going to need several investigations and these are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRI\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUS guided biopsy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPSMA PET scan\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct order is 1) \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E, 2) biopsy, 3) PSMA PET. The MRI will give information about location of an abnormality within the prostate, which is important for targeting that area with biopsy. An MRI also shows any suspicion of extraprostatic extension or seminal vesicle invasion. This is not well seen after a biopsy, as the biopsy causes inflammation around the prostate. The MRI does not confirm grade of cancer. The biopsy is needed to confirm malignancy, and to determine the cancer grade, volume and location (usually but not always where the MRI suggests).. Finally, a PSMA PET is used for staging of disease in lymph nodes and bones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA recent study (Kinnaird et al) has shown in a randomised controlled trial that microultrasonography-guided biopsy in patients with a clinical suspicion of carcinoma of the prostate is non-inferior to MRI-guided biopsy. MRI guided biopsy (in bore) is not done in Australia. In this country, MRI images are used to locate an abnormality and then an ultrasound to guided the needle to this area. This is called \u0022cognitive fusion biopsy\u0022, as opposed to MRI guided biopsy where the patient is on the MRI table and a needle is advanced and then the patient is reimaged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA PSMA-PET scan is used as part of the staging of prostate cancer - once the diagnosis has been established. Likewise, a whole body bone scan is a staging and not a diagnostic modality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine cytology may be done as part of the overall assessment, but it is not a diagnostic investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract ultrasound may provide information on bladder size and prostate pathology - but it lacks the diagnostic accuracy of MRI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multi-parametric MRI is now becoming the standard of practice in the initial assessment of a patient with suspected carcinoma of the prostate."],"references":["Wysock JS, Lepor H. Multi-parametric MRI imaging of the prostate\u2014implications for focal therapy. Transl Androl Urol 2017; 6:453-63.","Wise J. NICE recommends MRI for suspected prostate cancer to reduce biopsies. BMJ 2018;363:k5290.","O\u0027Shea A, Harisinghani M. PI\u2011RADS: multiparametric MRI in\u00a0prostate cancer. Magnetic Resonance Materials in Physics, Biology and Medicine 2022; 35:523\u201332","Kinnaird A, Luger F, Cash H, et al. Microultrasonography-Guided vs MRI-Guided Biopsy for Prostate Cancer Diagnosis The OPTIMUM Randomized Clinical Trial. JAMA. 2025; 333:1679-687."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"129"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T21:22:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T21:22:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"129"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103571"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","li